\par Lewis Orne clasped his hands behind his back until the knuckles showed white. He stared darkly out of his second-story window at a Hamal morning. The big yellow sun dominated a cloudless sky above distant mountains. It promised to be a scorcher of a day.

\par Behind him there was the sound of a scratchy stylus rasping across transmit-paper as the Investigation-Adjustment operative made notes on the interview they had just c
ompleted. The paper was transmitting a record of the words to the operative's waiting ship.
\par So }{\i\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 maybe I was wrong to push the panic button,}{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585  Orne thought.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 That doesn't give this wise guy the right to ride me!
\par After all, this is my first job. They can't expect perfection the first time out.}{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 
\par The scratching stylus began to wear on Orne's nerves.
\par Creases furrowed Orne's square forehead. He put his left hand up to the rough wooden window frame, ran his right hand through the stiff bristles of his close-cropped red hair. The loose cut of his white coverall uniform }{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 
\endash }{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585  standard for R&R agents }{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 \endash }{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 
 accentuated his blocky appearance. Blood suffused his full-jowled face. He felt himself vacillating between anger and the urge to give full vent to a pixie nature which he usually kept under control.
\par He thought: }{\i\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 
If I'm wrong about this place, they'll boot me out of the service. There's too much bad blood between R&R and Investigation-Adjustment. This I-A joker would just love to make us look stupid. But by god! There'll be some jumping if I'm right about Hamal!}{
\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 
\par Orne shook his head.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 But I'm probably wrong.}{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 
\par The more he thought about it, the more he felt it had been stupid to call in the I-A. Hamal probably was not aggressive by nature. Very likely there was no danger that R&R would provide the technological basis for arming a potential war maker.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 Still ...}{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 
\par Orne sighed. He felt a vague, dreamlike uneasiness. The sensation reminded him of the drifting awareness before awakening, the moments of clarity when action, thought and emotion combined.
\par Someone clumped down the stairs at the other end of the building. The floor shook beneath Orne's feet. This was an old building, the government guesthouse, built of rough lumber.
\par The room carried the sour smell of many former occupants and haphazard cleaning.
\par From his second-floor window Orne could see part of the cobblestone market square of this village of Pitsiben. Beyond the square he could make out the wide track of the ridge road that came up from the Plains of Rogga
. Along the road stretched a double line of moving figures: fanners and hunters coming for market day in Pitsiben. Amber dust hung over the road. It softened the scene, imparted a romantic out-of-focus look.
\par Farmers leaned into the pushing harnesses of the
ir low two-wheeled carts, plodding along with a heavy-footed swaying motion. They wore long green coats, yellow berets tipped uniformly over the left ear, yellow trousers, with cuffs darkened by the road dust, open sandals that revealed horny feet splayed
 out like the feet of draft animals. Their carts were piled high with green and yellow vegetables seemingly arranged to carry out the general pastel color scheme.
\par Brown-clothed hunters moved with the line, but at one side like flank guards. They strode alon
g, heads high, cap feathers bobbing. Each carried a bell-muzzled fowling piece at a jaunty angle over one arm, a spyglass in a leather case over the left shoulder. Behind the hunters trotted their apprentices pulling three-wheeled game carts overflowing w
ith tiny swamp deer, dappleducks and }{\i\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 porjos,}{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585  the snake-tailed rodents which Hamalites considered such a delicacy.
\par On the distant valley floor Orne could see the dark-red spire of the I-A ship that had come flaming down just after dawn on this day, homing on
 his transmitter. The ship, too, seemed set in a dream haze, its shape clouded by blue smoke from kitchen fires in the farm homes that dotted the valley. The ship's red shape towered above the homes, looking out of place, an ornament left over from holida
y decorations for giants.
\par As Orne watched, a hunter paused on the ridge road, unlimbered his spyglass, studied the I-A ship. The hunter appeared only vaguely curious. His action didn't fit expectations; it just didn't fit.
\par The smoke and hot yellow sun conspired to produce a summery appearance to the countryside }{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 \endash }{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 
 a look of lush growing behind pastel heat. It was essentially a peaceful scene, arousing in Orne a deep feeling of bitterness.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 Damn! I don't care what the I-A says. I was right to call them. These 
Hamalites are hiding something. They're not peaceful. The real mistake here was made by that dumbo on First-Contact when he gabbled about the importance we place on a peaceful history!}{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 
\par Orne grew aware that the scratching of the stylus had stopped. The I-A man cleared his throat.
\par Orne turned, looked across the low room at the operative.
\par The I-A agent sat at a rough table beside Orne's unmade bed.
\par Papers and folders were scattered all around him on the table.
\par A small recorder weighted one stack. The I-A man s
louched in a bulky wooden chair. He was big-headed, gangling and with overlarge features, a leathery skin. His hair was dark and straggling. The eyelids drooped. They gave to his face that look of haughty superciliousness that was like a brand mark of the
 I-A. The man wore patched blue fatigues without insignia. He had introduced himself as Umbo Stetson, chief I-A operative for this sector.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 The chief operative,}{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585  Orne thought.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 Why'd they send the chief operative?}{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585  Stetson noted Orne's attention, said: 'I believe we have most of it now. Let's just check it over once more for luck. You landed here ten weeks ago, right?'

\par 'Yes. I was set down by a landing boat from the R&R transport, Arneb Rediscovery.'
\par 'This was your first mission?'
\par 'I told you that. I graduated from Uni-Galacta with the class of '07, and did my apprentice work on Timurlain.'
\par Stetson frowned. 'Then they sent you right out here to this newly rediscovered backwater planet?'
\par 'That's right.'
\par 'I see. And you were full of the old rah-rah, the old missionary spirit to uplift mankind, all that sort of thing.'
\par Orne blushed, scowled.
\par Stetson nodded. 'I see they're still teaching that "cultural renaissance" bushwa at dear old Uni-Galacta.' He put a h
and to his breast, raised his voice in an elaborate caricature: 'We must reunite the lost planets with the centers of culture and industry, and take up the }{\i\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 glorious}{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 
 onward march of mankind that was cut off so brutally by the Rim Wars!'
\par He spat on the floor.
\par 'I think we can skip all that,' Orne muttered.
\par 'You're sooooo right,' Stetson said. 'Now, what'd you bring with you to this lovely vacation spot?'
\par 'I had a dictionary compiled by First-Contact, but it was pretty sketchy in ... '
\par 'Who was that First-Contact?'
\par 'Name on the dictionary says Andre Bullone.'
\par 'Oh }{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 \endash }{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585  Any relation to High Commissioner Bullone?'
\par 'I don't know.'
\par Stetson scribbled something on his papers. 'And that First-Contact report says this is a special place, a peaceful planet with a primitive farming-hunting economy, eh?'
\par That's right.'
\par 'Uh-huh. What else'd you bring into this garden spot?'
\par 'The usual stuff for my job and reports ... and a transmitter, of course.'
\par 'And you pushed the panic button on that transmitter two days ago, eh? Did we get here fast enough for you?'
\par Orne glared at the floor.
\par Stetson said: 'I suppose you've the usual eidetic memory crammed with cultural-medical-industrial-technological information.'
\par 'I'm a fully qualified R&R agent!'
\par 'We will observe a minute of reverent silence,' Stetson said.
\par Abruptly, he slammed a hand onto the table. 'It's a plain damn stupidity! Nothing but a political come-on!'
\par Orne snapped to angry attention. 'What?'
\par 'This R&R dodge, sonny. It's demagoguery, it's perpetuating a few political lives by e
ndangering all of us. You mark my words: We're going to rediscover one planet too many; we're going to give its people the industrial foundation they don't deserve; and we're going to see another Rim War to end all Rim Wars!'
\par Orne took a step forward, glaring. 'Why'n hell do you think I pushed the panic button?'
\par Stetson sat back, his calm restored by the outburst. 'My dear fellow, that's what we're now trying to determine.' He tapped his front teeth with the stylus. 'Now, just why }{\i\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 did}{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585  you call us?'
\par 'I }{\i\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585 told}{\fs20\cf1\insrsid15366585  you! It's ... ' He waved a hand at the window.
\par 'You felt lonely and wanted the I-A to come hold your hand, that it?'
\par 'Oh, go to hell!' Orne barked.
\par 'In due time, son. In due time.' Stetson's drooping eyelids drooped even farther. 'Now ... just what're they teaching you R&R dummies to look for these days?'
\par Orne swallowed another angry reply. 'War signs.'
\par 'What else? But let's be specific.'
